WEBVTT

00:00:26.000 --> 00:00:29.400 align:middle line:84%
>> Germs, bugs, thousands of
organisms are all around you

00:00:29.400 --> 00:00:30.367 align:middle line:90%
all the time.

00:00:30.367 --> 00:00:32.267 align:middle line:84%
That remote control
you're holding,

00:00:32.267 --> 00:00:35.900 align:middle line:84%
it's teeming with life,
bacteria, and other organisms.

00:00:35.900 --> 00:00:36.700 align:middle line:90%
>> Yuck!

00:00:36.700 --> 00:00:38.167 align:middle line:90%
>> Your microbiome.

00:00:38.167 --> 00:00:41.867 align:middle line:10%
[THEME MUSIC]

00:00:45.167 --> 00:00:47.200 align:middle line:84%
>> I have no idea
what a microbe is.

00:00:47.200 --> 00:00:48.033 align:middle line:90%
>> Something small.

00:00:48.033 --> 00:00:49.800 align:middle line:90%
>> It's-- it's micro.

00:00:54.567 --> 00:00:56.267 align:middle line:84%
>> I'm a man with
a huge world view.

00:00:56.267 --> 00:00:57.633 align:middle line:90%
I'm surrounded by microbes.

00:00:57.633 --> 00:00:58.433 align:middle line:90%
>> What am I?

00:00:58.433 --> 00:01:01.367 align:middle line:84%
>> You're the Helicobacter
pylori bacterium.

00:01:05.267 --> 00:01:09.267 align:middle line:84%
>> I want you to smell
yourselves, noses and armpits.

00:01:09.267 --> 00:01:12.767 align:middle line:10%
That is the smell
of your microbiome.

00:01:12.767 --> 00:01:14.433 align:middle line:90%
>> Microbiome?

00:01:14.433 --> 00:01:16.067 align:middle line:90%
>> Like a hotel for microbes?

00:01:16.067 --> 00:01:19.067 align:middle line:84%
>> Everybody, head
for the colon!

00:01:19.067 --> 00:01:20.867 align:middle line:84%
>> Then we get to
the large intestine.

00:01:20.867 --> 00:01:21.767 align:middle line:90%
>> They could be good.

00:01:21.767 --> 00:01:22.933 align:middle line:90%
They could be bad.

00:01:22.933 --> 00:01:24.900 align:middle line:90%
They're good and bad.

00:01:24.900 --> 00:01:27.067 align:middle line:84%
>> It all depends
on which one it is.

00:01:27.067 --> 00:01:29.900 align:middle line:84%
>> Well, young man, the truth is
we still don't know a lot about

00:01:29.900 --> 00:01:32.833 align:middle line:84%
the microbiome, but you
shouldn't let it freak you out.

00:02:05.467 --> 00:02:08.433 align:middle line:84%
>> My name is Maria
Gloria Dominguez-Bello.

00:02:08.433 --> 00:02:10.867 align:middle line:90%
People call me Gloria.

00:02:10.867 --> 00:02:12.867 align:middle line:90%
I'm a Microbiologist.

00:02:12.867 --> 00:02:17.300 align:middle line:84%
And my job is to study microbes,
the tiny organisms that

00:02:17.300 --> 00:02:18.433 align:middle line:90%
live inside us.

00:02:21.733 --> 00:02:26.000 align:middle line:84%
People hate germs,
another word for microbes,

00:02:26.000 --> 00:02:30.333 align:middle line:84%
but all life evolved from
them, and most are actually

00:02:30.333 --> 00:02:32.700 align:middle line:90%
good for us.

00:02:32.700 --> 00:02:35.067 align:middle line:84%
We call the ones
living inside us

00:02:35.067 --> 00:02:40.033 align:middle line:84%
our microbiome, a collection of
bacteria, viruses, and fungi.

00:02:44.033 --> 00:02:49.967 align:middle line:84%
They are involved in almost
everything our bodies do.

00:02:49.967 --> 00:02:53.067 align:middle line:84%
Microbes help us digest
food and make vitamins.

00:02:57.900 --> 00:03:01.200 align:middle line:84%
They train the immune system
to protect us against invaders.

00:03:05.667 --> 00:03:09.000 align:middle line:84%
They also determine, to
some extent, our response

00:03:09.000 --> 00:03:10.700 align:middle line:90%
to pain and our mood.

00:03:15.067 --> 00:03:20.267 align:middle line:84%
These discoveries have started
a scientific revolution.

00:03:20.267 --> 00:03:24.233 align:middle line:84%
But just as we are learning
how important they are,

00:03:24.233 --> 00:03:26.600 align:middle line:90%
our microbes are disappearing.

00:03:29.933 --> 00:03:33.467 align:middle line:84%
>> We have lost maybe as
much as 50% of our internal

00:03:33.467 --> 00:03:37.833 align:middle line:84%
biodiversity, and
this has consequences.

00:03:37.833 --> 00:03:39.867 align:middle line:90%
My name is Martin Blaser.

00:03:39.867 --> 00:03:42.967 align:middle line:84%
I'm a Professor of
Medicine and Microbiology.

00:03:42.967 --> 00:03:44.200 align:middle line:90%
>> Can I get a picture?

00:03:44.200 --> 00:03:45.033 align:middle line:90%
>> Yeah.

00:03:45.033 --> 00:03:47.567 align:middle line:84%
>> Over these last 20 years,
I've been thinking about this

00:03:47.567 --> 00:03:51.567 align:middle line:84%
idea, which I call the theory
of disappearing microbiota.

00:03:51.567 --> 00:03:54.633 align:middle line:84%
I wrote "Missing Microbes"
to sound an alarm.

00:03:54.633 --> 00:03:57.267 align:middle line:10%
>> Dr. Martin Blaser is the
author of "Missing Microbes."

00:03:57.267 --> 00:03:58.967 align:middle line:10%
>> Please welcome to the
program Martin Blaser.

00:03:58.967 --> 00:03:59.767 align:middle line:10%
Sir!

00:03:59.767 --> 00:04:03.333 align:middle line:10%
[APPLAUSE]

00:04:06.833 --> 00:04:09.867 align:middle line:84%
>> What's happening to our
internal ecology is very

00:04:09.867 --> 00:04:13.033 align:middle line:84%
similar to what's
happening to our climate.

00:04:13.033 --> 00:04:18.167 align:middle line:84%
But unfortunately, this
is happening even faster.

00:04:18.167 --> 00:04:22.400 align:middle line:84%
For decades now we have
seen many diseases rising,

00:04:22.400 --> 00:04:27.533 align:middle line:84%
and it's happening just as
we are losing our microbes.

00:04:27.533 --> 00:04:30.500 align:middle line:84%
>> Nearly 26 million people
in the US are living with

00:04:30.500 --> 00:04:31.300 align:middle line:90%
diabetes.

00:04:31.300 --> 00:04:34.100 align:middle line:10%
>> Why so many food allergies?

00:04:34.100 --> 00:04:36.200 align:middle line:10%
>> Asthma rates
rising dramatically.

00:04:36.200 --> 00:04:39.733 align:middle line:84%
>> More than 2/3 of Americans
are overweight or obese.

00:04:44.233 --> 00:04:47.167 align:middle line:84%
>> We're in the middle
of an extinction crisis.

00:04:47.167 --> 00:04:48.667 align:middle line:90%
It's invisible.

00:04:48.667 --> 00:04:50.567 align:middle line:90%
It's deadly.

00:04:50.567 --> 00:04:52.800 align:middle line:84%
And it's happening in
all of us right now.

00:05:05.767 --> 00:05:07.467 align:middle line:84%
People have been
worried about disease

00:05:07.467 --> 00:05:08.867 align:middle line:90%
since the beginning of time.

00:05:19.800 --> 00:05:22.867 align:middle line:84%
One of the most important
advances in human health

00:05:22.867 --> 00:05:26.433 align:middle line:90%
is having clean water.

00:05:26.433 --> 00:05:29.533 align:middle line:84%
And that has been
amazing because we

00:05:29.533 --> 00:05:33.067 align:middle line:84%
have less typhoid fever,
we have less cholera,

00:05:33.067 --> 00:05:36.767 align:middle line:90%
many other infections.

00:05:36.767 --> 00:05:40.200 align:middle line:84%
It was part of a revolution that
started about 200 years ago.

00:05:40.200 --> 00:05:43.467 align:middle line:84%
Scientists like Pasteur
discovered that many diseases

00:05:43.467 --> 00:05:45.433 align:middle line:90%
are caused by germs.

00:05:45.433 --> 00:05:47.667 align:middle line:84%
That was a tremendous
breakthrough.

00:05:50.500 --> 00:05:52.833 align:middle line:84%
We found ways that we
could fight these germs,

00:05:52.833 --> 00:05:56.967 align:middle line:84%
through sanitation, vaccines,
and through antibiotics.

00:05:56.967 --> 00:06:00.433 align:middle line:84%
And those were
remarkable victories.

00:06:00.433 --> 00:06:04.400 align:middle line:84%
Instead of knowing that if you
had five children, two of them

00:06:04.400 --> 00:06:06.500 align:middle line:84%
were going to die
in childhood, you

00:06:06.500 --> 00:06:09.500 align:middle line:84%
had the chance that all your
children were going to survive.

00:06:09.500 --> 00:06:12.167 align:middle line:84%
>> I went down to the library
to find out something else about

00:06:12.167 --> 00:06:14.067 align:middle line:90%
this field of antibiotics.

00:06:14.067 --> 00:06:18.233 align:middle line:10%
>> Antibiotics reached the
general public around 1945,

00:06:18.233 --> 00:06:22.000 align:middle line:10%
starting with penicillin and
then expanding from there.

00:06:22.000 --> 00:06:24.167 align:middle line:84%
>> America is continually
increasing its output

00:06:24.167 --> 00:06:27.267 align:middle line:84%
of penicillin, the new drug
that effects almost miraculous

00:06:27.267 --> 00:06:29.267 align:middle line:90%
cures.

00:06:29.267 --> 00:06:32.033 align:middle line:90%
>> It was the era of Superman.

00:06:32.033 --> 00:06:35.133 align:middle line:84%
During World War II,
when we beat our enemies,

00:06:35.133 --> 00:06:36.267 align:middle line:90%
we were invincible.

00:06:36.267 --> 00:06:37.767 align:middle line:90%
>> It's Superman!

00:06:37.767 --> 00:06:40.267 align:middle line:84%
>> These invaluable products
have been responsible

00:06:40.267 --> 00:06:42.567 align:middle line:84%
for saving millions
of human lives.

00:06:42.567 --> 00:06:45.667 align:middle line:84%
>> But we didn't understand that
there could be costs as well.

00:07:13.967 --> 00:07:17.667 align:middle line:84%
>> Why are so many chronic
diseases increasing so fast?

00:07:21.633 --> 00:07:29.100 align:middle line:84%
We seek answers in places where
the problem hasn't yet begun,

00:07:29.100 --> 00:07:32.967 align:middle line:84%
where we work with people who
live more like our ancestors did.

00:07:37.533 --> 00:07:42.100 align:middle line:84%
Venezuela is my
country of birth.

00:07:42.100 --> 00:07:44.967 align:middle line:84%
For over 20 years, I've
been returning there

00:07:44.967 --> 00:07:47.667 align:middle line:84%
and making trips to
villages deep in the jungle.

00:08:01.400 --> 00:08:04.933 align:middle line:84%
Sometimes, we are the first
Western doctors and scientists

00:08:04.933 --> 00:08:08.867 align:middle line:84%
they've ever met, and we
take that responsibility

00:08:08.867 --> 00:08:12.500 align:middle line:84%
very seriously because we
are aware of the history

00:08:12.500 --> 00:08:13.833 align:middle line:90%
of exploitation.

00:08:19.667 --> 00:08:22.033 align:middle line:84%
The villagers'
traditional lifestyle

00:08:22.033 --> 00:08:25.967 align:middle line:84%
is a safe place
for their microbes.

00:08:25.967 --> 00:08:31.267 align:middle line:84%
They don't have chlorinated
water or pasteurized milk.

00:08:31.267 --> 00:08:34.867 align:middle line:90%
Their foods are never processed.

00:08:34.867 --> 00:08:38.333 align:middle line:84%
They have low exposure to
chemicals and antibiotics.

00:08:41.000 --> 00:08:45.267 align:middle line:84%
All of this keeps their
microbiome healthy and rich.

00:08:45.467 --> 00:08:48.900 align:middle line:90%
Everyone's eating fruit.

00:08:49.333 --> 00:08:52.767 align:middle line:84%
Our kids grew up eating
what I plant.

00:08:55.333 --> 00:08:58.933 align:middle line:84%
>> We explained to the villagers
that they have more microbial

00:08:58.933 --> 00:09:04.700 align:middle line:84%
diversity than us and there is
much we can learn from them.

00:09:04.700 --> 00:09:06.933 align:middle line:84%
(WOMEN SPEAKING
IN YANOMAMÖ LANGUAGE)

00:09:06.967 --> 00:09:08.567 align:middle line:90%
Karawasoma?

00:09:08.600 --> 00:09:10.067 align:middle line:90%
They're not here.

00:09:10.100 --> 00:09:11.100 align:middle line:90%
Calme?

00:09:11.133 --> 00:09:13.167 align:middle line:90%
She's here. Carmen.

00:09:13.200 --> 00:09:15.133 align:middle line:90%
Ah, Carmen, Carmen.

00:09:15.167 --> 00:09:20.733 align:middle line:84%
They will take samples
from your mouth.

00:09:21.733 --> 00:09:26.200 align:middle line:84%
>> When we ask them
for stool samples...

00:09:26.233 --> 00:09:26.167 align:middle line:90%
Can you bring that poop sample here?

00:09:26.200 --> 00:09:28.800 align:middle line:84%
...sometimes they
laugh and they say,

00:09:28.800 --> 00:09:31.933 align:middle line:84%
did you come all this
way just to see my poop?

00:09:31.933 --> 00:09:38.333 align:middle line:84%
And we say, yes, because
your poop contains trillions

00:09:38.333 --> 00:09:41.733 align:middle line:84%
of tiny organisms
that may help us

00:09:41.733 --> 00:09:45.367 align:middle line:84%
find the answers to some of
the world's biggest health problems.

00:09:48.833 --> 00:09:51.967 align:middle line:84%
This is also important
for them because they

00:09:51.967 --> 00:09:53.567 align:middle line:90%
are integrating very fast.

00:09:57.700 --> 00:10:00.433 align:middle line:84%
So studying their
microbes before they

00:10:00.433 --> 00:10:03.500 align:middle line:84%
lose them is a
race against time.

00:10:08.500 --> 00:10:15.233 align:middle line:90%
>> [SPEAKING YANOMAMÖ]

00:10:15.233 --> 00:10:18.967 align:middle line:84%
>> The samples are kept at
minus 80 degrees and transported

00:10:18.967 --> 00:10:23.267 align:middle line:84%
to Caracas until they
can be sent to the US.

00:10:23.267 --> 00:10:27.133 align:middle line:84%
Then we study them in the
lab and store them safely

00:10:27.133 --> 00:10:29.333 align:middle line:90%
for the future.

00:10:29.333 --> 00:11:14.000 align:middle line:10%
[SINGING IN SPANISH]

00:11:14.000 --> 00:11:17.967 align:middle line:90%
[MUSIC PLAYING]

00:11:26.500 --> 00:11:27.367 align:middle line:90%
>> Hi, Ingsheng.

00:11:27.367 --> 00:11:27.967 align:middle line:90%
Hi, Antonia.

00:11:27.967 --> 00:11:28.800 align:middle line:90%
>> Good morning.

00:11:36.100 --> 00:11:42.767 align:middle line:84%
>> These are all off
one side in the Amazon.

00:11:42.767 --> 00:11:46.500 align:middle line:84%
Ever since I was a little kid,
I wanted to be a scientist.

00:11:50.733 --> 00:11:54.067 align:middle line:10%
My childhood in Venezuela
was a happy life,

00:11:54.067 --> 00:12:00.800 align:middle line:10%
close to nature with farm
animals, fruits, and trees.

00:12:00.800 --> 00:12:04.667 align:middle line:84%
One year, my parents
gave me a chemistry set.

00:12:04.667 --> 00:12:09.967 align:middle line:84%
I loved the colorful
powders and smelly liquids.

00:12:09.967 --> 00:12:14.033 align:middle line:84%
Our second bathroom was my lab,
and nobody could enter there.

00:12:17.367 --> 00:12:20.867 align:middle line:90%
I went to university in Caracas.

00:12:20.867 --> 00:12:25.433 align:middle line:84%
In grad school, I studied
how cows can eat toxic plants

00:12:25.433 --> 00:12:27.500 align:middle line:90%
and survive.

00:12:27.500 --> 00:12:30.900 align:middle line:84%
And that's when I got interested
in how microbes affect us.

00:12:35.333 --> 00:12:39.333 align:middle line:84%
In Venezuela, I had
Adriana in 1991.

00:12:39.333 --> 00:12:42.167 align:middle line:90%
Allow me to introduce Adriana.

00:12:42.167 --> 00:12:51.267 align:middle line:84%
>> Then I moved to
New York in 2012.

00:12:51.267 --> 00:12:54.933 align:middle line:84%
This is not the
traditional way, of course.

00:12:54.933 --> 00:12:57.667 align:middle line:90%
Want to try?

00:12:57.667 --> 00:12:58.967 align:middle line:90%
I'm making more.

00:12:58.967 --> 00:12:59.800 align:middle line:90%
>> Mmm.

00:12:59.800 --> 00:13:01.667 align:middle line:90%
That's delicious.

00:13:01.667 --> 00:13:04.067 align:middle line:90%
>> We met through work.

00:13:04.067 --> 00:13:06.333 align:middle line:90%
I work with his colleagues.

00:13:06.333 --> 00:13:08.367 align:middle line:84%
>> On her last day,
I had just come back,

00:13:08.367 --> 00:13:11.200 align:middle line:84%
and we met really
for 10 minutes.

00:13:11.200 --> 00:13:13.333 align:middle line:84%
And then we actually
started doing work together.

00:13:13.333 --> 00:13:15.067 align:middle line:90%
We collaborated together.

00:13:15.067 --> 00:13:16.033 align:middle line:90%
>> Are you leaving?

00:13:16.033 --> 00:13:16.833 align:middle line:90%
>> No, you are.

00:13:16.833 --> 00:13:19.100 align:middle line:90%
>> I'm leaving in one minute.

00:13:19.100 --> 00:13:24.733 align:middle line:84%
>> I was divorced, and we
started a friendship that ended

00:13:24.733 --> 00:13:27.233 align:middle line:90%
in a deeper relation.

00:13:27.233 --> 00:13:29.967 align:middle line:10%
>> NYU Hospital here in
Manhattan was plunged

00:13:29.967 --> 00:13:31.900 align:middle line:10%
into darkness, its
generators failing.

00:13:31.900 --> 00:13:36.167 align:middle line:10%
>> We were getting very close,
and then came Hurricane Sandy.

00:13:36.167 --> 00:13:39.300 align:middle line:84%
I was the Chief of
Medicine at NYU.

00:13:39.300 --> 00:13:43.200 align:middle line:84%
I got a phone call that said we
have to evacuate the hospital.

00:13:43.200 --> 00:13:46.900 align:middle line:84%
And she said, well, if you're
going, I'm going with you.

00:13:46.900 --> 00:13:47.867 align:middle line:10%
We came home.

00:13:47.867 --> 00:13:49.700 align:middle line:90%
It was early in the morning.

00:13:49.700 --> 00:13:53.233 align:middle line:84%
And I thought to
myself, who would I

00:13:53.233 --> 00:13:54.767 align:middle line:90%
rather spend my life with?

00:13:54.767 --> 00:13:57.533 align:middle line:84%
So that's when I
proposed to Gloria.

00:13:57.533 --> 00:13:59.633 align:middle line:84%
>> I didn't ask him
to go on his knee.

00:13:59.633 --> 00:14:00.900 align:middle line:90%
[CHUCKLING]

00:14:00.900 --> 00:14:03.900 align:middle line:90%
But I said yes.

00:14:03.900 --> 00:14:05.600 align:middle line:84%
Don't touch my hand
in public, Marty.

00:14:05.600 --> 00:14:06.533 align:middle line:90%
>> Why not?

00:14:06.533 --> 00:14:08.967 align:middle line:90%
[CHUCKLES]

00:14:08.967 --> 00:14:10.667 align:middle line:90%
I was a city kid.

00:14:10.667 --> 00:14:13.100 align:middle line:90%
I grew up in Queens.

00:14:13.100 --> 00:14:17.000 align:middle line:84%
I've kind of been
exploring all my life.

00:14:17.000 --> 00:14:20.533 align:middle line:84%
I rode on freight
trains, in boxcars.

00:14:20.533 --> 00:14:23.700 align:middle line:84%
They say that the
first time you pee off

00:14:23.700 --> 00:14:25.467 align:middle line:84%
the side of a boxcar
you're hooked.

00:14:28.067 --> 00:14:31.433 align:middle line:84%
Actually, I wanted to
become an architect,

00:14:31.433 --> 00:14:33.933 align:middle line:84%
but I discovered
at a very early age

00:14:33.933 --> 00:14:36.633 align:middle line:90%
that I had no talent for that.

00:14:36.633 --> 00:14:40.633 align:middle line:84%
I went into the specialty of
infectious diseases trying

00:14:40.633 --> 00:14:45.733 align:middle line:84%
to solve very complex problems,
patients who are very ill.

00:14:45.733 --> 00:14:49.900 align:middle line:10%
I was really interested
in questioning why.

00:14:49.900 --> 00:14:52.367 align:middle line:84%
And at a certain
point, I found out

00:14:52.367 --> 00:14:54.967 align:middle line:84%
that I could answer some
of my own questions,

00:14:54.967 --> 00:14:59.800 align:middle line:90%
and that was very exciting.

00:14:59.800 --> 00:15:02.133 align:middle line:84%
>> So are you going to
the VA first or Bellevue?

00:15:02.133 --> 00:15:02.933 align:middle line:90%
>> Bellevue.

00:15:02.933 --> 00:15:06.700 align:middle line:90%
[MUSIC PLAYING]

00:15:10.500 --> 00:15:12.533 align:middle line:84%
I believe the
hypothesis is correct,

00:15:12.533 --> 00:15:16.233 align:middle line:84%
that antibiotics are
contributing to the rise of all

00:15:16.233 --> 00:15:17.933 align:middle line:90%
these diseases.

00:15:17.933 --> 00:15:20.467 align:middle line:84%
But not everybody
believes that's correct.

00:15:20.467 --> 00:15:24.667 align:middle line:84%
And so the job of a scientist
is to examine questions and see

00:15:24.667 --> 00:15:26.900 align:middle line:84%
if we can find more
evidence that it's true

00:15:26.900 --> 00:15:29.567 align:middle line:84%
and try to understand
the details.

00:15:29.567 --> 00:15:32.500 align:middle line:84%
Maybe it's true for some
diseases, but not others.

00:15:36.467 --> 00:15:38.633 align:middle line:84%
And that's why we do
experiments in the lab

00:15:38.633 --> 00:15:41.033 align:middle line:84%
to try to understand,
how does it work?

